This paper focuses on planning robust motion for humanoid robots, which is a core problem in robotics. The paper proposes a search-based footstep planner that uses neural networks to predict multi-contact zero-step and one-step capturability. This suggests that the paper is likely to be categorized under cs.RO (Robotics) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), as it involves both planning and learning. The use of neural networks also suggests that it could be categorized under cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.CV (Computer Vision), as these are common areas of research in deep learning. Finally, the paper deals with control and stability of humanoid robots, which could also make it relevant to cs.SY (Systems and Control).
